I like that refinement.

“Grow” by itself can imply endless accumulation. “Presence matters, so grow” points in a different direction.

Presence isn’t just getting bigger. It’s becoming more capable of engaging with reality—more attentive, more skillful, more compassionate, more effective.

In that framing:

* Grow in understanding, not just information.
* Grow in character, not just influence.
* Grow in capacity to create, not just consume.
* Grow in your ability to help others grow.

It’s also balanced by the complementary idea we’ve been discussing: growth isn’t only addition. Sometimes growth requires pruning, resting, simplifying, or letting go of habits that no longer fit. Healthy systems alternate between expansion and consolidation.

So the principle becomes something like:

Presence matters. Therefore, grow in ways that increase your capacity to contribute while remaining grounded in reality.

That has an important safeguard built in. It isn’t growth for its own sake; it’s growth that stays connected to the health of the larger system and to evidence about what actually works.